===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|braiden|lang=enm}}, {{term|breiden|lang=enm}}, {{term|bræiden|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|breġdan||to move quickly, pull, shake, swing, throw (wrestling), draw (sword), drag; bend, weave, braid, knit, join together; change color, vary, be transformed; bind, knot; move, be pulled; flash}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*bregdaną||to flicker, flutter, jerk, tug, twitch, flinch, move, swing}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*bʰrēḱ-}}, {{term/t|ine-pro|*bʰrēǵ-||to shine, shimmer}}. Cognate with Scots {{term|brade|lang=sco}}, {{term|braid||to move quickly or suddenly|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|breidzje|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|breien||to knit|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|breiden|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|bar|-}} {{term|bretten||to move quickly, twitch|lang=bar}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|bregða||to move quickly, jerk|lang=is}}.

